 Marathon explosions") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Boston") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Chechnya") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Massachusetts") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "US crime") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "United States") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Russia") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "World news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Europe") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "News") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 13:07:16 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/boston-suspect-dzhokhar-tsarnaev-school") (dc:creator nil "Miriam Elder") (dc:subject nil "World news") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T13:27:15Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407515475") (media:keywords nil "Boston Marathon explosions, Boston, Chechnya, Massachusetts, US crime, United States, Russia, World news, Europe") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366376597142/Dzhokhar-Tsarnaev-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "AFP/Getty Images") (media:description nil "Dzhokhar Tsarnaev, a suspect in the Boston Marathon bombing who being hunted by police in the suburb of Watertown. Photograph: AFP/Getty Images")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366376603573/Dzhokhar-Tsarnaev-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "AFP/Getty Images") (media:description nil "Dzhokhar Tsarnaev, a suspect in the Boston Marathon bombing who is being hunted by police in the suburb of Watertown. Photograph: AFP/Getty Images")))) ("MIT police officer killed in shooting named as Sean Collier, 26" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/99603?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Amit-police-officer-sean-collier-killed%3A1896607&ch=World+news&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Boston+Marathon+bombing+%28News%29%2CBoston+%28US+news%29%2CMIT+Massachusetts+Institute+of+Technology%2CWorld+news%2CUS+news%2CCrime+%28US%29&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful&c6=Amanda+Holpuch&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+04%3A45&c8=1896607&c9=Article&c10=&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=US&c65=MIT+police+officer+killed+in+shooting+named+as+Sean+Collier%2C+26&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FWorld+news%2FBoston+Marathon+bombing\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Authorities said Collier, who had worked on the MIT police force for about a year, was shot multiple times in his car on Thursday<br /><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/boston-mit-police-dead-watertown\">Follow the latest updates in our Boston live blog</a></p><p>An officer with the Massechusetts Institute of Technology police, Sean Collier, 26, was identified as the victim of a shooting at the university amid a manhunt for the Boston bombing suspects.</p><p>The Middlesex district attorney's office said Collier was shot multiple times in his car on Thursday night. He was pronounced dead at Massachusetts General Hospital.</p><p>\"Sean was one of these guys who really looked at police work as a calling,\" <a href=\"http://web.mit.edu/newsoffice/2013/victim-identified-as-sean-collier-0419.html\">MIT police chief John DiFava said in a statement</a>. \"He was born to be a police officer.\"</p><p>Collier had served on the MIT police force since 9 January 2012. He was also a member of the school's Outing Club, which organizes outdoor activities for the university community. \"In a very short period of time, it was remarkable how engaged he was with students, particularly graduate students,\" DiFava said.</p><p>Previously, Collier was a civilian employee at the Somerville police department, just north of Boston. He was raised in the north-eastern Massachusetts city of Wilmington, and was single.</p><p>The shooting took place at about 10.30pm. Shortly after, police received reports of an armed car-jacking on the MIT campus in Cambridge.</p><p>In a statement released Friday, MIT said it was \"heartbroken\" by the news. \"Our thoughts are now with the family,\" MIT said. The school cancelled classes, and employees were urged not to come to campus. The school dedicated its website to the officer on Friday – the homepage is now mainly black and includes a large image of the MIT police badge. </p><p>Isabel Ruiz, the MIT executive vice-president and treasurer, and chancellor Eric Grimson, sent a letter to members of the MIT community. It read: \"While the circumstances around the officer's death remain the subject of an active investigation, what is certain is that the officer gave his life to defend the peace of our campus. His sacrifice will never be forgotten by the Institute. We are thinking now of his family, and our hearts are heavy.\"</p><p>Collier was a member of the WAKA Kickball league of greater Boston. <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/WAKAKickballBoston/posts/474325819300454\">The league said in a statement</a> it was heartbroken by the loss of Collier. \"Many of us knew Sean as a kickballer, who played on Sunday afternoons with his team Kickhopopotamus. Our thoughts and prayers go out him, his family, friend, teammates, and those who knew him.\"</p><p>Collier received a criminal justice degree from Salem State university in 2009 and graduated with honors. <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=497716476944387&id=118242334891805\">The school said</a>: \"Our thoughts and sympathy go out to Sean's family as well as all those affected by the recent tragic events in Boston.\"</p><p>A Boston metro transit officer was injured in a separate incident connected to the search for the bombing suspects on Thursday night. The officer, Richard H Donahue Jr, 33, underwent surgery on Friday morning.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston-marathon-explosions\">Boston Marathon bombing</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston\">Boston</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/education/mit-massachusetts-institute-of-technology\">MIT - Massachusetts Institute of Technology</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/usa\">United States</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/us-crime\">US crime</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/amanda-holpuch\">Amanda Holpuch</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/mit-police-officer-sean-collier-killed" (20849 26247) old 11 nil nil ((title nil "MIT police officer killed in shooting named as Sean Collier, 26") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/mit-police-officer-sean-collier-killed") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/99603?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Amit-police-officer-sean-collier-killed%3A1896607&ch=World+news&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Boston+Marathon+bombing+%28News%29%2CBoston+%28US+news%29%2CMIT+Massachusetts+Institute+of+Technology%2CWorld+news%2CUS+news%2CCrime+%28US%29&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful&c6=Amanda+Holpuch&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+04%3A45&c8=1896607&c9=Article&c10=&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=US&c65=MIT+police+officer+killed+in+shooting+named+as+Sean+Collier%2C+26&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FWorld+news%2FBoston+Marathon+bombing\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Authorities said Collier, who had worked on the MIT police force for about a year, was shot multiple times in his car on Thursday<br /><br />• <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/boston-mit-police-dead-watertown\">Follow the latest updates in our Boston live blog</a></p><p>An officer with the Massechusetts Institute of Technology police, Sean Collier, 26, was identified as the victim of a shooting at the university amid a manhunt for the Boston bombing suspects.</p><p>The Middlesex district attorney's office said Collier was shot multiple times in his car on Thursday night. He was pronounced dead at Massachusetts General Hospital.</p><p>\"Sean was one of these guys who really looked at police work as a calling,\" <a href=\"http://web.mit.edu/newsoffice/2013/victim-identified-as-sean-collier-0419.html\">MIT police chief John DiFava said in a statement</a>. \"He was born to be a police officer.\"</p><p>Collier had served on the MIT police force since 9 January 2012. He was also a member of the school's Outing Club, which organizes outdoor activities for the university community. \"In a very short period of time, it was remarkable how engaged he was with students, particularly graduate students,\" DiFava said.</p><p>Previously, Collier was a civilian employee at the Somerville police department, just north of Boston. He was raised in the north-eastern Massachusetts city of Wilmington, and was single.</p><p>The shooting took place at about 10.30pm. Shortly after, police received reports of an armed car-jacking on the MIT campus in Cambridge.</p><p>In a statement released Friday, MIT said it was \"heartbroken\" by the news. \"Our thoughts are now with the family,\" MIT said. The school cancelled classes, and employees were urged not to come to campus. The school dedicated its website to the officer on Friday – the homepage is now mainly black and includes a large image of the MIT police badge. </p><p>Isabel Ruiz, the MIT executive vice-president and treasurer, and chancellor Eric Grimson, sent a letter to members of the MIT community. It read: \"While the circumstances around the officer's death remain the subject of an active investigation, what is certain is that the officer gave his life to defend the peace of our campus. His sacrifice will never be forgotten by the Institute. We are thinking now of his family, and our hearts are heavy.\"</p><p>Collier was a member of the WAKA Kickball league of greater Boston. <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/WAKAKickballBoston/posts/474325819300454\">The league said in a statement</a> it was heartbroken by the loss of Collier. \"Many of us knew Sean as a kickballer, who played on Sunday afternoons with his team Kickhopopotamus. Our thoughts and prayers go out him, his family, friend, teammates, and those who knew him.\"</p><p>Collier received a criminal justice degree from Salem State university in 2009 and graduated with honors. <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=497716476944387&id=118242334891805\">The school said</a>: \"Our thoughts and sympathy go out to Sean's family as well as all those affected by the recent tragic events in Boston.\"</p><p>A Boston metro transit officer was injured in a separate incident connected to the search for the bombing suspects on Thursday night. The officer, Richard H Donahue Jr, 33, underwent surgery on Friday morning.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston-marathon-explosions\">Boston Marathon bombing</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston\">Boston</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/education/mit-massachusetts-institute-of-technology\">MIT - Massachusetts Institute of Technology</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/usa\">United States</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/us-crime\">US crime</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/amanda-holpuch\">Amanda Holpuch</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Boston Marathon bombing") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Boston") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/education")) "MIT - Massachusetts Institute of Technology") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "World news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "United States") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "US crime") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Editorial") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 15:45:11 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/mit-police-officer-sean-collier-killed") (dc:creator nil "Amanda Holpuch") (dc:subject nil "World news") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T15:45:11Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407527713") (media:keywords nil "Boston Marathon bombing, Boston, MIT - Massachusetts Institute of Technology, World news, United States, US crime") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366381892825/MIT-Patrol-Officer-Sean-A-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "MIT/REUTERS") (media:description nil "MIT Patrol Officer Sean A Collier, 26, of Somerville, Massachusetts was shot in an altercation with the suspects in the Boston Marathon bombing late Thursday night Photograph: MIT/REUTERS")) (media:content ((height . "537") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366381936887/MIT-Patrol-Officer-Sean-A-001.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "MIT/REUTERS") (media:description nil "Sean Collier. MIT said in a statement: 'His sacrifice will never be forgotten by the Institute.' Photograph: MIT/Reuters")))) ("Chechnya's centuries-long bloody strife goes global | Stephen Kinzer" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/82058?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Achechnya-centuries-long-bloody-strife-global%3A1896637&ch=Comment+is+free&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Chechnya%2CRussia+%28News%29%2CLeo+Tolstoy+%28Author%29%2CWorld+news%2Cal-Qaida+%28News%29%2CTerrorism+-+international%2CVladimir+Putin%2CBoston+%28US+news%29%2CBoston+Marathon+bombing+%28News%29%2CMassachusetts+%28News%29%2CUS+news&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful&c6=Stephen+Kinzer&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+05%3A04&c8=1896637&c9=Blog&c10=Comment&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=Comment+is+free&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Chechnya%27s+centuries-long+bloody+strife+goes+global&c66=Comment+is+free&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FComment+is+free%2FComment+is+free%2Fblog%2FComment+is+free\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">To Tolstoy, fighting Chechen rebels in the 1850s, they were a 'hardy thistle' defying suppression. Now, it has seeded itself afar</p><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/boston-mit-police-dead-watertown\">Although nothing is yet known about</a> what motivated the <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/boston-lockdown-bombings-suspect\">two young Chechen men, Dzhokhar and Tamerlan Tsarnaev, suspected of carrying out the bombing of the Boston Marathon on Monday</a>, one thing is clear: Chechnya is as potent a generator of violence today as it has been for blood-soaked centuries.</p><p>This <a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/early-lead/wp/2013/04/19/boston-marathon-explosions-live-updates-3/?hpid=z2#liveblog-entry-13227\">small Russian republic, nestled in the mountainous Caucasus, has produced</a> some of the world's most implacable fighters and most ruthless terrorists. Other places are also generators of far-flung violence beyond their own borders – Pakistan and Saudi Arabia are obvious examples – but none has as long a history of war, resistance, and terror as Chechnya.</p><p>The history of Chechnya is one of imperialism gone terribly wrong. In the 13th and 14th centuries, Chechens were among the few peoples to fend off Mongol conquerors, but at a terrible cost. Turks, Persians, and Russians sought to seize Chechnya, and it was finally absorbed into the Russian Empire in 1859.</p><p>Chechens are not ethnically or culturally Russian, and have now been fighting for generations to free themselves from Russian rule. Russian attempts to suppress Chechen separatism have even made a contribution to world literature, in the form of Leo Tolstoy's masterful novella, <a href=\"http://ebooks.adelaide.edu.au/t/tolstoy/leo/t65h/index.html\">Hadji Murad</a>, which the critic Harold Bloom has called \"my personal touchstone for the sublime of prose fiction, to me the best story in the world.\"</p><p>Tolstoy served with a Cossack regiment assigned to fight Chechens in the 1850s – a stark reminder of how long this conflict has festered. A hardy plant, the thistle, is for Tolstoy the perfect symbol of Chechnya and its \"desperately brave\" rebels.</p><p>\"What vitality!\" a Russian soldier marvels as he contemplates a thistle at the end of the story:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Man has conquered everything and destroyed millions of plants, yet this one won't submit.</p></blockquote><p>During the second world war, Stalin accused the Chechens of collaborating with the Nazis – a credible charge, since Chechens will ally themselves with anyone who might help them throw off Russian rule. He deported the entire Chechen population to Siberia and Kazakhstan. Tens of thousands died before he permitted their return after the war.</p><p>The end of the Soviet Union brought not respite to the long conflict, but a ruinous intensification of it. Today, Russia – driven by the steely will of President Vladimir Putin – is as determined as ever to crush the insurgency without granting Chechens any form of autonomy or self-rule, much less independence.</p><p>This has led some Chechens to take the path of terror. They are held responsible for crimes that make the Boston Marathon bombing seem like child's play – most of them outside Chechnya. <a href=\"http://www.cfr.org/terrorism/chechen-terrorism-russia-chechnya-separatist/p9181#p6\">Among the attacks attributed to or claimed by Chechen rebels</a> are the 1999 bombing of a Moscow shopping center, in which 64 people were killed; the 2002 siege of a theater, also in Moscow, that resulted in 120 deaths; the 2004 attack on a school in the town of Beslan, in which 380 people, nearly all of them children, were slaughtered; and just three years ago, an attack on the Moscow subway system by two female suicide bombers that killed 39.</p><p>Russia has fought this long conflict with their own kind of savagery. <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First_Chechen_War#The_Russian_war_in_Chechnya\">Russian forces have killed tens of thousands of Chechens since the 1990s</a>, and leveled Grozny, the Chechen capital, in the 1994-95 phase of the conflict. A separatist leader, Shamil Basayev, allegedly the planner of the Beslan school massacre, was assassinated in 2004, evidently by Russian security forces. That same year, President Putin named a local ally, Ramzan Kadyrov, to run Chechnya for him. </p><p><a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/the-president-again-turns-a-blind-eye-to-russias-misdeeds/2013/04/17/4186d3c4-a5ed-11e2-8302-3c7e0ea97057_story.html\">According to many outsiders, including the US State Department</a>, Kadyrov has become one of the world's most brutal figures, responsible for widespread torture in secret prisons and many murders. He \"has been implicated personally\", according to State, in the murder of the crusading journalist Anna Politkovskaya in 2006.</p><p>Chechens decided long ago not to confine their struggle to Chechnya. Some have fought against American-backed armies in Afghanistan and Iraq. In return, foreign militants have turned up in the ranks of Chechen rebels. The US State Department has also reported that some <a href=\"http://www.cfr.org/terrorism/chechen-terrorism-russia-chechnya-separatist/p9181#p7\">funding for the rebels comes from sources linked to al-Qaida</a>.</p><p>This conflict is ethnic and political, but it has a religious overlay. Chechens are Muslim, and some share the belief that the west is engaged in a global campaign against Islam. They have decided that their response should also be global. George Bush's global \"war on terror\" has found its corollary: a globalised campaign of terror.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/chechnya\">Chechnya</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/russia\">Russia</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/leonikolaevichtolstoy\">Leo Tolstoy</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/al-qaida\">al-Qaida</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/terrorism\">Global terrorism</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/vladimir-putin\">Vladimir Putin</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston\">Boston</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston-marathon-explosions\">Boston Marathon bombing</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/massachusetts\">Massachusetts</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/usa\">United States</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/stephenkinzer\">Stephen Kinzer</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2013/apr/19/chechnya-centuries-long-bloody-strife-global" (20849 27422) old 15 nil nil ((title nil "Chechnya's centuries-long bloody strife goes global | Stephen Kinzer") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2013/apr/19/chechnya-centuries-long-bloody-strife-global") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/82058?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Achechnya-centuries-long-bloody-strife-global%3A1896637&ch=Comment+is+free&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Chechnya%2CRussia+%28News%29%2CLeo+Tolstoy+%28Author%29%2CWorld+news%2Cal-Qaida+%28News%29%2CTerrorism+-+international%2CVladimir+Putin%2CBoston+%28US+news%29%2CBoston+Marathon+bombing+%28News%29%2CMassachusetts+%28News%29%2CUS+news&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful&c6=Stephen+Kinzer&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+05%3A04&c8=1896637&c9=Blog&c10=Comment&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=Comment+is+free&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Chechnya%27s+centuries-long+bloody+strife+goes+global&c66=Comment+is+free&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FComment+is+free%2FComment+is+free%2Fblog%2FComment+is+free\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">To Tolstoy, fighting Chechen rebels in the 1850s, they were a 'hardy thistle' defying suppression. Now