 (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366388571283/Texas-Department-of-Publi-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "RON T. ENNIS/AP") (media:description nil "Texas Department of Public Safety Sgt Jason Reyes, left, talks to reporters in West, Texas. Photograph: RON T. ENNIS/AP")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366388580003/Texas-Department-of-Publi-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "RON T. ENNIS/AP") (media:description nil "Texas Department of Public Safety Sergeant Jason Reyes, left, talks to reporters in West, Texas. Photograph: Ron T Ennis/AP")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366388777722/Searchers-in-protective-s-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Fort Worth Star-Telegram/MCT via Getty Images") (media:description nil "Searchers in protective suits walk through the blast zone of the fertilizer plant that exploded in West, Texas. Photograph: Fort Worth Star-Telegram/MCT via Getty Images")))) ("FAA places no-fly zone over Boston as manhunt continues" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/16111?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aboston-no-fly-zone%3A1896661&ch=World+news&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Boston+Marathon+bombing+%28News%29%2CBoston+%28US+news%29%2CUS+news%2CAir+transport+%28News%29&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2Cflightexclusion&c6=Dominic+Rushe&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+05%3A28&c8=1896661&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=US&c65=FAA+places+no-fly+zone+over+Boston+as+manhunt+continues&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FWorld+news%2FBoston+Marathon+bombing\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Federal agency imposes 'temporary flight restriction' over city similar to Monday's, adding to lockdown on transport system</p><p>Planes have been banned from flying over Boston, as a manhunt continues in the wake of the <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston-marathon-explosions\">bomb attacks at the finishing line of the city's marathon on Monday</a>.</p><p>The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) imposed a 3.5-nautical-mile \"temporary flight restriction\" over the city on Friday, to ensure a \"safe environment for law-enforcement activities\" <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/boston-mit-police-dead-watertown\">as police searched for a second suspect</a>. The restriction applies to all aircraft flying below 3,000 feet, according to an FAA bulletin. Similar measures were imposed after the bombing on Monday.</p><p>Much of Boston's transport system is now in lockdown as police continue their search for <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/boston-suspect-dzhokhar-tsarnaev-school\">Dzhokhar Tsarnaev, the 19-year-old suspect</a>, following the death of <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/tamerlan-tsarnaev-american-life-of-dead-boston-bomb-suspect\">his brother Tamerlan</a>. The Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority has shut the city's subway, bus and ferries following a police request. Amtrak also suspended rail service between Boston and Providence.</p><p>Boston's Logan international airport was operating normally under heightened security, according to airport spokesman Matthew Brelis. \"The FAA directive is not affecting operations. The airport is open and operating under heightened security,\" said Brelis. </p><p>He said that many of the airlines had waived fees for those flying to and from Boston who were not comfortable with using the airport during the manhunt. JetBlue, Logan's busiest carrier, canceled change fees for Boston customers and said flights were continuing.</p><p>\"At this time, Boston airport remains open for operations and we're running at a normal pace,\" JetBlue said in a statement. \"We will continue to monitor the situation and will adjust as necessary. Our primary concern is the safety and well-being of our customers and crew members.\"</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston-marathon-explosions\">Boston Marathon bombing</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston\">Boston</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/usa\">United States</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/air-transport\">Air transport</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/dominic-rushe\">Dominic Rushe</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/boston-no-fly-zone" (20849 28816) old 14 nil nil ((title nil "FAA places no-fly zone over Boston as manhunt continues") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/boston-no-fly-zone") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/16111?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aboston-no-fly-zone%3A1896661&ch=World+news&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Boston+Marathon+bombing+%28News%29%2CBoston+%28US+news%29%2CUS+news%2CAir+transport+%28News%29&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2Cflightexclusion&c6=Dominic+Rushe&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+05%3A28&c8=1896661&c9=Article&c10=News&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=US&c65=FAA+places+no-fly+zone+over+Boston+as+manhunt+continues&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FWorld+news%2FBoston+Marathon+bombing\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Federal agency imposes 'temporary flight restriction' over city similar to Monday's, adding to lockdown on transport system</p><p>Planes have been banned from flying over Boston, as a manhunt continues in the wake of the <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston-marathon-explosions\">bomb attacks at the finishing line of the city's marathon on Monday</a>.</p><p>The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) imposed a 3.5-nautical-mile \"temporary flight restriction\" over the city on Friday, to ensure a \"safe environment for law-enforcement activities\" <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/boston-mit-police-dead-watertown\">as police searched for a second suspect</a>. The restriction applies to all aircraft flying below 3,000 feet, according to an FAA bulletin. Similar measures were imposed after the bombing on Monday.</p><p>Much of Boston's transport system is now in lockdown as police continue their search for <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/boston-suspect-dzhokhar-tsarnaev-school\">Dzhokhar Tsarnaev, the 19-year-old suspect</a>, following the death of <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/tamerlan-tsarnaev-american-life-of-dead-boston-bomb-suspect\">his brother Tamerlan</a>. The Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority has shut the city's subway, bus and ferries following a police request. Amtrak also suspended rail service between Boston and Providence.</p><p>Boston's Logan international airport was operating normally under heightened security, according to airport spokesman Matthew Brelis. \"The FAA directive is not affecting operations. The airport is open and operating under heightened security,\" said Brelis. </p><p>He said that many of the airlines had waived fees for those flying to and from Boston who were not comfortable with using the airport during the manhunt. JetBlue, Logan's busiest carrier, canceled change fees for Boston customers and said flights were continuing.</p><p>\"At this time, Boston airport remains open for operations and we're running at a normal pace,\" JetBlue said in a statement. \"We will continue to monitor the situation and will adjust as necessary. Our primary concern is the safety and well-being of our customers and crew members.\"</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston-marathon-explosions\">Boston Marathon bombing</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/boston\">Boston</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/usa\">United States</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/air-transport\">Air transport</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/dominic-rushe\">Dominic Rushe</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Boston Marathon bombing") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Boston") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "United States") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Air transport") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "News") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 16:28:00 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/apr/19/boston-no-fly-zone") (dc:creator nil "Dominic Rushe") (dc:subject nil "World news") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T16:44:14Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407531960")